# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aex-index
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Following aggressive international expansion, ABN AMRO was acquired and broken up in 2007–2008 by a consortium of European banks, including Fortis which intended to take over its formed operations in the Benelux region.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Fortis came under stress in the autumn of 2008, and was in turn broken up into separate national entities; the Dutch operations, namely Fortis Bank Nederland and the former ABN AMRO activities that Fortis had planned to absorb, were nationalized, restructured, and renamed ABN AMRO in mid-2010.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 20 November 2015, the Dutch government publicly re-listed the company through an IPO and sold 20 percent of the shares to the public.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO has been designated as a Significant Institution since the entry into force of European Banking Supervision in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the European Central Bank.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 1824, King William I established the Nederlandsche Handel-Maatschappij (NHM) a trading company to revive trade and financing of the Dutch East Indies and it would become one of the primary ancestors of ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The NHM merged with the *Twentsche Bank* in 1964, to form Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN).
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Also in 1964, the *Amsterdamsche Bank*, established in 1871, merged with the *Rotterdamsche Bank*, established in 1873 (as part of a merger that included *Determeijer Weslingh & Zn.* from 1765), to form Amsterdamsche en Rotterdamsche Bank, known as AMRO Bank.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 22 September 1991, ABN and AMRO merged to form ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 1993, two of its investment banking subsidiaries ― Bank Mees & Hope and Pierson, Heldring & Pierson ― merged in turn to form MeesPierson.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The two merged banks brought to ABN AMRO a large network of overseas companies and branches.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] From NHM, ABN owned a significant branch network in Asia and the Middle East, including the Saudi Hollandi Bank owned by the NHM Jeddah branch.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Another, the Hollandsche Bank-Unie (HBU), which grew from the merger of the *Hollandsche Bank voor de Middellandsche Zee* (HBMZ) and the *Hollandsche Zuid-Amerika Bank* in 1933, gave ABN AMRO an extensive network of branches in South and Central America.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 1979, ABN had expanded into North America with the acquisition of Chicago-based LaSalle National Bank.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 2005, Standard Federal became *LaSalle Bank Midwest* to unite ABN AMRO's two banking networks in the U.S.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 1995, ABN AMRO purchased The Chicago Corporation, an American securities and commodities trading and clearing corporation.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Other major acquisitions included the Brazilian bank Banco Real in 1998, and the Italian bank Antonveneta in 2006.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] It was also involved in the controversial acquisition of the Dutch local government mortgage and building development organisation, the Bouwfonds in 2000.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO sold the Bouwfonds as a going concern in 2006.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In July 2006, Favonius Ventures, which was founded and headed by Roel Pieper, received all of the technology investments of ABN AMRO Capital which is the private equity business unit of ABN AMRO Bank N.V.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had come to a crossroads in early 2005.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The bank had still not come close to its own target of having a return on equity that would put it among the top five of its peer group, a target that the CEO, Rijkman Groenink had set upon his appointment in 2000.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] From 2000 until 2005, ABN AMRO's stock price stagnated.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Financial results in 2006 added to concerns about the bank's future.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Operating expenses increased at a greater rate than operating revenue, and the efficiency ratio deteriorated further to 69.9%.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Non-performing loans increased considerably year on year by 192%.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Net profits were only boosted by sustained asset sales.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In 2006, research findings were publicly released regarding ABN AMRO Bank N.V.'s predecessors and connections to African slavery.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] An examination of 200 predecessors of ABN AMRO Bank N.V. founded before 1888 determined that some had connections to African slavery, either in the United States or elsewhere in the Americas.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] By 2007, ABN AMRO was the second-largest bank in the Netherlands and the eighth-largest in Europe by assets.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] At that time, the magazine *The Banker* and Fortune Global 500 placed it 15th in the list of world's biggest banks and it had operations in 63 countries, with over 110,000 employees.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Pakistan merged with Prime Commercial Bank which consisted of 69 branches across 24 cities.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank (Pakistan) Limited (Which later got merged into Royal Bank of Scotland Pakistan) was formed as the result of the US$227 million acquisition.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 21 February 2007, The Children's Investment Fund Management (TCI) hedge fund called to ask the Chairman of the Supervisory Board to actively investigate a merger, acquisition, or breakup of ABN AMRO, stating that the current stock price did not reflect the true value of the underlying assets.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] TCI asked the chairman to put its request on the agenda of the annual shareholders' meeting to be held in April 2007.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Events accelerated on 20 March 2007, when the British bank Barclays and ABN AMRO both confirmed they were in exclusive talks about a possible merger.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 28 March 2007, ABN AMRO published the agenda for the shareholders' meeting of 2007.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] It included all items requested by TCI, but with the recommendation not to follow the request for a breakup of the company.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] According to the proposed deal, RBS would receive ABN's United States operations, LaSalle, and ABN's wholesale operations; Banco Santander would take the Brazilian operations; and Fortis, the Dutch operations.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The three banks set up a joint venture, RFS Holdings (with a name based on their respective initials), to execute the transaction.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 23 April, ABN AMRO and Barclays announced the proposed acquisition of ABN AMRO by Barclays.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The deal was valued at €67 billion and included the sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America for €21 billion.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Two days later, the RBS-led consortium brought out its indicative offer, worth €72 billion, if ABN AMRO would abandon its sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] During the shareholders' meeting the next day, approximately 68 percent of the shareholders voted in favor of the breakup as requested by TCI.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The sale of LaSalle was seen as obstructive by many: as a way of blocking the RBS bid, which hinged on further access to the US markets, in order to expand on the success of the group's existing American brands, Citizens Bank and Charter One.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 3 May 2007, the Dutch Investors' Association (Vereniging van Effectenbezitters), with the support of shareholders representing up to 20 percent of ABN's shares, took its case to the Dutch commercial court in Amsterdam, seeking an injunction against the LaSalle sale.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The court ruled that the sale of LaSalle could not be viewed apart from the current merger talks of Barclays with ABN AMRO and that the ABN AMRO shareholders should be able to approve other possible merger/acquisition candidates in a general shareholder meeting.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] However, in July 2007, the Dutch Supreme Court ruled that Bank of America's acquisition of LaSalle Bank could proceed and Bank of America absorbed LaSalle effective 1 October 2007.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 23 July 2007, Barclays raised its offer for ABN AMRO to €67.5bn, after securing investments from the governments of China and Singapore, but it was still short of the RBS consortium's offer.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Barclay's revised bid was worth €35.73 a share — 4.3% more than its previous offer.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The offer, which included 37% cash, remained below the €38.40-a-share offer made the week before by the RFS consortium.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The revised offer did not include an offer for La Salle Bank since ABN AMRO could proceed with the sale of that subsidiary to Bank of America.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] RBS would now settle for ABN's investment-banking division and its Asian Network.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 30 July 2007, ABN AMRO withdrew its support for Barclays' offer which was lower than the offer from the group led by RBS.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] While the Barclays offer matched ABN AMRO's "strategic vision," the board couldn't recommend it from "a financial point of view." The US$98.3bn bid from RBS, Fortis, and Banco Santander was 9.8% higher than Barclays' offer.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Barclays Bank withdrew its bid for ABN AMRO on 5 October, clearing the way for the RBS-led consortium's bid to go through, along with its planned dismemberment of ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] RFS formally acquired ABN AMRO on 17 October 2007.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Fortis would receive ABN AMRO's Dutch and Belgian operations, Banco Santander would get Banco Real in Brazil, and Banca Antonveneta in Italy and RBS would get ABN AMRO's wholesale division and all other operations, including those in Asia.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Both RBS and Fortis were increasingly visibly overextended following the ABN AMRO acquisition.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 22 April 2008, RBS announced the largest rights issue in British corporate history, which aimed to raise £12billion in new capital to offset a writedown of £5.9billion resulting from the bad investments and to shore up its reserves following the purchase of ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 11 July 2008, Fortis CEO Jean Votron stepped down after the ABN AMRO deal had depleted Fortis's capital.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The total worth of Fortis, as reflected by its stock value, was at that time one-third of what it had been before the acquisition, and just under the value it had paid for the Benelux activities of ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 3 October 2008, Fortis was nationalised.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The Dutch government bought a number of Fortis divisions plus Fortis's share in ABN AMRO for EUR 16.8 billion.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] It subsequently announced that the parts of ABN AMRO it had acquired would be integrated with Fortis Bank Nederland (FBN) to create a new ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 13 October 2008, British Prime Minister Gordon Brown announced a UK government bailout of the financial system.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The Treasury would infuse £37 billion ($64 billion, €47 billion) of new capital into Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc, Lloyds TSB and HBOS Plc, to avert financial sector collapse.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] This resulted in a total government ownership in RBS of 58%.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] As a consequence of this rescue, the chief executive of the group Fred Goodwin offered his resignation, which was duly accepted.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Later in October, Fortis announced that it would sell its stake in RFS Holdings, which included all activities that had not been transferred yet to Fortis (i.e. everything except asset management).
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In September 2009, RBS rebranded the Morgans sharedealing business in Australia as RBS Morgans.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] This followed the rebranding of the ABN AMRO Australia unit to RBS Australia in March that year.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 10 February 2010, RBS announced that branches it owned in India and the United Arab Emirates were to be rebranded under its name.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] HSBC Holdings said it would buy the Indian retail and commercial banking businesses of Royal Bank of Scotland for $1.8bn, however the deal fell-through in December 2012.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The operations owned by Santander, notably those in Italy and Brazil, were merged with Santander, sold or eliminated.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The Dutch government had obtained full control of all Fortis operations in the Netherlands, including those parts of ABN-AMRO then belonging to Fortis, at a price of €16.8bn.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The government and the De Nederlandsche Bank president have announced the merger of Dutch Fortis and ABN AMRO parts will proceed while the bank is in state ownership.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] This was completed in July 2010, when Fortis operations in the Netherlands were rebranded ABN AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In November 2008, a Belgian court dismissed a suit by shareholders of Fortis objecting to the Belgian government's handling of the Fortis/ABN AMRO transaction and subsequent break-up.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The Dutch government appointed former Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm as CEO to restructure and stabilise the bank, and in February 2010 the assets it owned were legally demerged from those owned by RBS.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] This demerger created two separate organisations, ABN AMRO Bank N.V. and The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The former was merged with ABN AMRO Private Banking, Fortis Bank Nederland, the private bank MeesPierson (formerly owned by the original ABN AMRO and Fortis) and the diamond bank International Diamond & Jewelry Group to create ABN AMRO Group N.V., with the Fortis name being dropped on 1 July 2010.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The remaining parts of the original ABN AMRO still owned by The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V., meanwhile, were renamed, sold or closed.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] As part of the agreement with the European Commission on state aid in the restructuring, ABN AMRO sold Hollandsche Bank-Unie to Deutsche Bank in April 2010, together with another subsidiary, IFN Finance.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO acquired the specialist on-line mortgage provider *Direktbank Hypotheken* as part of the nationalisation and from 1 January 2011, it stopped selling these products under this brand to the public.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] It absorbed the mortgage business into its own products under the ABN AMRO brand as well as Florius brand.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In November 2020, ABN AMRO announced it would cut 2800 jobs and sell its head offices as a plan to reduce costs, hoping to save €700 million by 2024.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In December 2023, ABN AMRO acquired BUX to boost its digital presence for an undisclosed amount.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In May 2024, ABN AMRO agreed to buy Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe (HAL), a German private bank specialised in wealth management, for 672 million euros ($730 million) from Chinese conglomerate Fosun International.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In October 2024, the Dutch government announced its plan to reduce its stake in ABN AMRO from 40.5% to 30% in the coming months.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] On 12 November 2025, ABN AMRO announced the acquisition of Dutch lender NIBC Bank for 960 million euros from American private equity firm Blackstone.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank has offices in 15 countries with 32,000 employees, most of whom are based in the Netherlands with only 5,000 in other countries.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] Its operations include a private banking division which focuses on high-net-worth clients in 14 countries as well as commercial and merchant banking operations that play a major role in energy, commodities and transportation markets as well as brokerage, clearing, and custody.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In April 2022, ABN AMRO Bank announced the company had signed a multi-year subscription extension with Switzerland based Banking and financial software development organisation Temenos.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The deal was made to support ABN AMRO with customer growth and overall business expansion on the Temenos Banking cloud.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The bank refers to itself as ABN AMRO in all capitals, based on an acronym of the two originating banks names Algemene Bank Nederland and the Amsterdam and Rotterdam Bank, in the second case the first two letters of each city make up the word AMRO.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The letters in 'ABN' are pronounced separately and 'AMRO' is pronounced as a word.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] For this reason some media spell the name as 'ABN Amro'.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In written text both versions are used, although the bank itself uses only the uppercase version.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] In conversations, the bank is sometimes referred to as simply ABN or AMRO bank depending on one's location around the world.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The green and yellow shield logo was designed by Landor Associates for ABN AMRO in 1991, and has been used as a brand for the bank and all its subsidiaries.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was the main sponsor of Dutch football club AFC Ajax of Amsterdam from 1991 to 2008.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The sponsor logo was at the time the only one in the world to be printed vertically down the right hand side of the front of the shirt.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] As of 2014, ABN AMRO is one of the strategic industry partners with Duisenberg School of Finance.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The bank's former art collection has been managed since the end of 2007 by a dedicated foundation, the Stichting ABN AMRO Kunstverzameling.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] As a result of the alleged fraud by Bernard Madoff, Fortis Bank Netherlands (Holding) NV lost 1 billion euros on loans from the bank (through its subsidiary Prime Fund Solutions, part of Fortis Merchant Banking) to hedge fund and as collateral investments in Bernard Madoff Investment Securities.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The Dutch government said on behalf of Fortis that a claim against the Securities and Exchange Commission would be considered.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was mentioned by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) in court filings when it sued Goldman Sachs and one of Goldman's collateralized debt obligation (CDO) traders on 16 April 2010.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] The SEC alleges that Goldman defrauded both IKB Deutsche Industriebank and ABN AMRO by its failure to disclose that the CDOs it sold to both banks were not assembled by a third party, but instead through the guidance of a hedge fund that was counterparty in the CDS transaction.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] This hedge fund, Paulson & Co., stood to reap great financial benefit in the event of default.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO bank is one of the main banks financing the diamond business.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had branches in Botswana, New York, Hong Kong, Mumbai and Dubai, all of which they have sold or are in process of closing.
[src:aex-index/abn-amro] They currently only have a branch in Antwerp, where they are also shrinking their business.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The **AEX index**, derived from **Amsterdam Exchange index**, is a stock market index composed of Dutch companies that trade on Euronext Amsterdam, formerly known as the *Amsterdam Stock Exchange*.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Started in 1983, the index is composed of a maximum of 30 of the most frequently traded securities on the exchange.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] It is one of the main national indices of the stock exchange group Euronext alongside Euronext Brussels' BEL20, Euronext Dublin's ISEQ 20, Euronext Lisbon's PSI-20, the Oslo Bors OBX Index, and Euronext Paris's CAC 40.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The AEX started from a base level of 100 index points on 3 January 1983 (a corresponding value of 45.378 is used for historic comparisons due to the adoption of the Euro).
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The index's peak to date was set on 26 October 2021 816.91 After the dot-com bubble in 1999, the index value more than halved over the following three years before recovering in line with most global financial markets.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The AEX index dealt with its second largest one-day loss on 12 March 2020, when the index closed down almost 11% during the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The AEX index enjoyed its third largest one-day loss on 29 September 2008, when the index closed down almost 9%.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The decade between 1998 and 2008 was bad for the AEX index, as it was the worst performing stock index except for the OMX Iceland 15.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The preceding years were a lot better compared to the rest of the world.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The following table shows the annual development of the AEX index since 1983.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] As of 2011, the AEX index composition is reviewed four times a year - a full "annual" review in March and interim "quarterly" reviews in June, September and December.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Any changes made as a result of the reviews take effect on the third Friday of the month.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Previously reviews were held in March and September only.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Prior to 2008, index changes were made only annually in March.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] At the main March review date, the 23 companies listed on Euronext Amsterdam's regulated market with the highest share turnover (in Euros) over the previous year are admitted to the index.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Of the companies ranked between 24th and 27th, a further two are selected with preference given to existing constituents of the index.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Companies which have fewer than 25% of shares considered free float on Euronext Amsterdam are, however, ineligible for inclusion.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] Unlike some other European benchmark equity indices (such as the OMXS30), if a company has more than one class of shares traded on the exchange, only the most frequently traded of these will be accepted into the AEX.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] If a company or companies are removed from the index due to delisting, acquisition or another reason, no replacements are made until the next review date.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] At the three interim reviews in June, September and December, no changes are made to the AEX unless either the index has seen one or more constituents removed, or a non-constituent possesses a share turnover ranked 15th or higher overall over the previous 12 months.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] If vacancies are to be filled, the highest-ranking non-AEX companies are selected to join the index.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The AEX is a capitalization-weighted index.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] At each main annual review, the index weightings of companies in the index are capped at 15%, but range freely with share price subsequently.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The index weights are calculated with respect to the closing prices of the relevant companies on 1 March.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] At the interim reviews, weightings after adjustment are left as close as possible to those of the previous day and are not re-capped.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The index comprises a basket of shares, the numbers of which are based on the constituent weights and index value at the time of readjustment.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The AEX Index is traded as a future on the Euronext Equities & Index Derivatives exchange (EUREID) under the ticker symbol FTI.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The size of each contract is 200 EURO x AEX Index points (e.g.
[src:aex-index/aex-index] The index is composed of the following listings as of 31 December 2024.
[src:aex-index/amx-index] The **AMX index**, derived from Amsterdam Midkap Index, also known as Midkap index or simply Midkap, is a stock market index composed of Dutch companies that trade on Euronext Amsterdam, formerly known as the *Amsterdam Stock Exchange*.
[src:aex-index/amx-index] It is composed of the 25 funds that trade on the exchange and that rank 26–50 in size.
[src:aex-index/amx-index] The funds that rank 1–25 in size are represented in the AEX index.
[src:aex-index/amx-index] As of June 2021 the AMX index has the following composition.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The **ASE Market Capitalization Weighted Index** is a stock index of the Amman Stock Exchange in Jordan.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The **ASE Weighted Index** is one of two principal stock indices on the exchange, the other being the ASE Unweighted Price Index.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The **ASE Unweighted Index** was created in 1980 and was very successful.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The ASE went on to create a weighted index in 1992.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The weighted index, whose constituents are listed below, attaches a value to each stock price based on the total market capitalisation of each stock; that is, the total amount of money the stock is worth on the stock market.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The Unweighted Index calculates an index value based on the price alone.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] Both the weighted and unweighted indices use the same list of stocks.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The constituents of the ASE indices are evaluated each year.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The 70 stocks listed here are the 2007 version of the index.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] They are categorized by sector: banking sector, insurance sector, service sector and industrial sector.
[src:aex-index/ase-market-capitalization-weighted-index] The lists are alphabetized by stock symbol.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The company was founded by Arthur del Prado (1931–2016) in 1964.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] From 2008 until 2020, son of Arthur del Prado, Chuck del Prado was CEO.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM pioneered important aspects of many established wafer-processing technologies used in industry, including lithography, deposition, ion implantation, single-wafer epitaxy, and in recent years atomic layer deposition.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Semiconductor equipment companies ASML, ASM Pacific Technology (ASMPT) and Besi are former divisions of ASM.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM headquarters is located in Almere, the Netherlands.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The company has R&D sites in Almere (the Netherlands), Helsinki (Finland), Leuven (Belgium, near IMEC), Phoenix (Arizona), Tama (Japan), and Dongtan (South Korea).
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Manufacturing primarily occurs in Singapore and Dongtan (South-Korea).
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM also has sales & service offices across the globe, including United States, South Korea, China, Taiwan, Japan, Singapore and Israel.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] As of 2021, it has 3,312 staff, located in 14 countries.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The shares of the company are listed on the Euronext Amsterdam.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In March 2020, ASM was promoted to the AEX index.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM has a minority stake in ASM Pacific Technology, a Hong Kong–based company active in semiconductor assembly, packaging and surface-mount technology.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] To create a semiconductor chip, many individual steps are performed using various types of wafer processing equipment, including photolithographic patterning, depositing thin layers, etching to remove material, thermal treatments, and other steps.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM's systems are designed for deposition processes, when thin films, or layers, of various materials are grown or deposited onto the wafer.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Many different thin-film layers are deposited to complete the full sequence of process steps necessary to manufacture a chip.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM's technology development is driven by its customers' goal to build faster, cheaper, and more powerful semiconductor chips with reduced energy consumption.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] This goal drives the need to shrink the dimensions of components on the chip, targeting to double the number of components per unit area on a chip every two years (Moore's law).
[src:aex-index/asm-international] As part of this scaling of dimensions, ASM supplies its customers – chip manufacturers – with machines that deposit ever thinner films of semiconductor materials.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM also develops deposition processes for new materials to be used in semiconductor fabrication.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] During the past 15 years, an increasing array of new materials has been introduced in the fabrication of chips.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] These new materials were required to achieve the necessary performance improvements of chips, as outlined by Moore's Law.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] For instance, in 2007 in a MOSFET transistor, the silicon oxidegate dielectric was replaced with a high-κ, a material that has a higher dielectric constant than silicon oxide.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In this particular case, ASM pioneered the chemical process and theanew deposition method called atomic layer deposition after nearly a decade of R&D.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In addition, increasingly precise deposition methods are required as components on a chip such as transistors moved from planar to 3D structures, like FinFETs in the past decade.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM has a leading position in single wafer atomic layer deposition (ALD).
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM offers a number of methods and accompanying machines to deposit these thin films of materials.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The company tries to expand the applicability of its deposition technologies and machines as much as possible.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In 2021, the company spent 151 million euro on R&D (or 9% of its annual revenues).
[src:aex-index/asm-international] R&D activities stretch from basic research of new materials to the application of new materials in chip manufacturing.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM designs and sells both single-wafer deposition tools, in which the process is performed one wafer at a time, as well as so-called batch tools, in which the deposition is performed on multiple wafers at a time.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The prices of the company's systems varies, but typically are multiple of million euros per system.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] ASM sells its equipment to semiconductor manufacturers worldwide, with the majority of its revenues from Asian customers.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In 2021, 1.41 billion euro of the total 1.73 billion euro in revenues was generated through equipment sales, the rest came from spares and service.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Shares of ASM are traded on the Euronext stock exchange since 1996.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Since March 2020, ASM is included on the AEX index.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] The market capitalization of ASM Pacific Technology is no longer consolidated after ASM's interest in ASM Pacific Technology decreased to 25 percent in 2013.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Between 1981 and 2015 ASM was also listed on the Nasdaq.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In 2018 share price averaged at €48.62 resulting in an average market capitalization of 2.53 billion euro.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] In 2019 average closing price was €68.98, resulting in an average market capitalization of 3.38 billion euro.
[src:aex-index/asm-international] Market capitalization at year-end 2021 was 18.88 billion euro, based on the closing share price of €388.70 on Euronext Amsterdam on December 31, 2021.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML was founded in 1984 as a joint venture between the Dutch technology companies Philips and ASM International; it became an independent publicly traded entity four years later.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Having been established to complete development of Philips' previously in-house project to produce their own lithography machine, ASML initially had no market-ready products.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Furthermore, ASML's first product, the PAS 2000, was a commercial and technical failure; however, the company did attain commercial success during the early 1990s with the PAS 5500.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] During 1997, ASML began studying the potential shift to EUV.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By 2002, the company had become the largest supplier of lithography machines.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] While sales were negatively impacted by the start of the Great Recession in 2008, ASML had effectively recovered by 2011.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In July 2012, Intel purchased a 15 percent stake in ASML in exchange for $4.1 billion; Samsung and TSMC also bought stakes in the firm under a co-investment program.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML completed development of its EUV machines in the late 2010s.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] During the 2010s and 2020s, both the US and Dutch governments imposed new oversight and restrictions on each individual sale of ASML technology to China.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML's corporate headquarters is in Veldhoven, just outside the city of Eindhoven in the Netherlands, and is the location for research, development, manufacturing, and assembly.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML employs more than 42,000 people from 143 nationalities and relies on a network of nearly 5,000 tier 1 suppliers.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML has a worldwide customer base and over 60 service points in 16 countries.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] It has offices in the Netherlands, the United States, Belgium, France, Germany, Ireland, Israel, Italy, the United Kingdom, China, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Singapore, and Taiwan.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The company is listed on both the Euronext Amsterdam and Nasdaq stock exchanges, as ASML.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] It is also a component of the Euro Stoxx 50 and Nasdaq-100.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML can be traced back to the 1970s and the Dutch electronics company Philips.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By the early 1980s, Philips had projected that considerable additional investment would be necessary to complete its development, but this need came at a time in which the company was trying to reduce expenditure.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Accordingly, in 1984, the company elected to spin-off its lithography machine activities into a joint venture with another Dutch firm, ASM International, which specialised in the supply of equipment to the semiconductor industry.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] This decision shaped the machine as well, which adopted a modular design and used clearly defined subsystems.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Early on, ASML struggled to secure business, having no market share and no brand recognition at the start of its operations.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Furthermore, the firm's first product, the PAS 2000, was a commercial and technical failure, having used oil pressure (instead of electric motors) to move the wafer during exposure, which had a tendency to leak; future lithograph machines made by ASML would use conventional electric motors instead.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By the start of 1988, Philips was reportedly considered shutting down the joint venture entirely after ASM International, however, sufficient support was present on Philip's board to continue with operations, giving ASML the time to develop another lithography machine, the PAS 5500.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Accordingly, in 1988, ASML became an independent publicly traded entity; that same year, it first adopted the name ASML, which is its official name and not an abbreviation.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 1991, ASML released the PAS 5500, which quickly became the company's first commercial breakout.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In contrast to the more precise contemporary lithography machines from competing firm Nikon, the modular design used by ASML meant that its machines could be fixed quickly on site, reducing downtime and making it possible to extend the machine’s operating life.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The serviceability advantage was reportedly the key factor that led to IBM ordering the PAS 5500 over its Japanese counterparts.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The first company to operate the PAS 5500 was Micron Technology, one of the world's largest producers of computer memory and storage; it became ASML's largest customer for a time.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The success of the PAS 5500 line propelled ASML into a period of intense competition with both Canon and Nikon, who were the leaders of the lithography market at the time.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 1997, ASML began studying a shift to using extreme ultraviolet.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Two years later, it joined a consortium, which included Intel and two other U.S. chipmakers, in order to exploit fundamental research conducted by the US Department of Energy.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Because the Cooperative Research and Development Agreement (CRADA) it operates under is funded by the US government, licensing must be approved by Congress.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Furthermore, in return for being permitted to join this consortium, ASML committed to the establishment of a US-based research center and to source 55 percent of components for all machines sold in the US from American suppliers.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML collaborated with various manufacturers to obtain mirrors, including the Belgian firms IMEC and Sematech as well as Germany's Carl Zeiss.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 2001, ASML acquired the US-based lithography equipment manufacturer Silicon Valley Group (SVG) after it had encountered liquidity issues, The SVG acquisition, which has also been licensed for EUV research results, involved ASML in an arrangement to supply 193 nm scanners to Intel.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 2002, it became the largest supplier of photolithography systems.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Aided by the adoption of the dual-stage TWINSCAN architecture to reduce idle time, ASML machines could produce more chips per hour than any competitor's products; this competitive edge was so strong that the company could charge higher prices for their machines and still grow its market share.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By the end of the decade, it had secured two thirds of the global lithography market and had become the dominant supplier for the growing smartphone market.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] During December 2006, ASML announced the acquisition of rival firm BRION Technologies in exchange for $270 million; this transaction into direction competition with the major EDA vendors who had similar products - Cadence Design Systems, Synopsys, and Mentor Graphics.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML had recovered by 2011, reporting record-high revenue for that year.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] During the early 2010s, ASML sharply increased its annual R&D budget, rising from just under $500 million in 2010 to $1 billion in 2015.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] While this expenditure was necessary in order to complete the development of its next generation EUV machines, financing such amounts was not straightforward.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] To achieve this, ASML launched a co-investment program in 2012, under which 23 percent of the company was sold to its three largest customers: Intel, TSMC and Samsung.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Intel's investment into $4.1 billion into ASML, made in July 2012, gave it a 15 percent stake in the company; this move was stated to accelerate Intel's transition from 300 mm to 450 mm wafers as well as support further development of EUV lithography.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] That same month, ASML offered another 10 percent of its shares to other companies.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Beyond simply generating additional funds, these new stakeholders were incentivised to participate in ASML's research efforts.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] TSMC in particular worked closely with ASML to develop and troubleshoot its EUV machines, being keen to use them to manufacture their own products.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] As part of their EUV strategy, ASML announced the acquisition of DUV and EUV sources manufacturer Cymer in exchange for $2.55 billion in October 2012; this transaction was completed in May 2013.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Cymer's technology was viewed as being useful to developing ASML's EUV machines.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In November 2013, ASML paused development of 450 mm lithography equipment, citing uncertain timing of chipmaker demand.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In early 2015, ASML reported an instance of intellectual property theft; allegedly a number of employees had been found stealing confidential data from its Silicon Valley software subsidiary that develops software for machine optimization.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Three years later, ASML was awarded $223 million in damages pertaining to this incident, as well as securing the offending company's own intellectual property.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML employees have often been viewed as highly desirable recruitment targets for other tech companies.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In June 2016, ASML announced their plans to acquire Taiwan-based Hermes Microvision Inc. in exchange for about $3.1 billion; it was reported that this transaction would secure technology for creating smaller and more advanced semiconductors.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 2018, the Trump administration tried to block the sale of ASML technology to China.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] This move, which has been viewed as part of a wider "technological cold war" between the US and China, may have contributed to the 2020–2023 global chip shortage and impacted the business opportunities available to ASML.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In July 2020, ASML stated that it had acquired the German optical glassmaking firm Berliner Glas Group, which will help to satisfy the increasing need for components for its EUV systems; at the time of this acquisition, ASML's outstanding orders had reportedly risen to €10 billion.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In July 2021, European Commissioner Thierry Breton, visited ASML and announced a goal of at least 20 percent of global production of semiconductors in Europe by 2030, and support via a European Alliance on semiconductors.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] After reporting earnings in July 2021, the company said they had a near monopoly for machines used by TSMC and Samsung to make the advanced chips.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In February 2023, ASML claimed that a former worker in China "allegedly" stole information about the company's technology.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] This was not the first time that ASML was allegedly linked with an intellectual property breach connected to China.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In its 2021 annual report, ASML mentioned that Dongfang Jingyuan Electron Limited "was actively marketing products in China that could potentially infringe on ASML's IP rights." At the time, the United States Department of Commerce expressed concern about economic espionage against ASML.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In October 2023, Dutch newspaper NRC Handelsblad reported that the former employee who "allegedly" stole data about ASML's technology subsequently went to work for Huawei.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In March 2023, the Dutch government placed restrictions on chip equipment exports in order to protect national security.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] This measure affected ASML as one of the most important companies in the global microchip supply chain.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Export license requirements came into effect in September 2023.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Three months later, the Netherlands' Institute for Human Rights ruled that despite the country's constitution prohibiting discrimination based on nationality, ASML was allowed to reject job applications from residents of countries subject to sanctions under the U.S.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Export Administration Regulations (such as China, Cuba, Iran, North Korea, and Syria) in order to remain compliant with U.S. law.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In January 2024, the Dutch government placed further restrictions on the shipment of some advanced chip-making equipment to China.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] On 6 September 2024, the Dutch government tightened export controls on certain ASML chipmaking equipment, aligning its policy with U.S. restrictions to limit China's access to advanced technology amid safety and geopolitical concerns.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] These restrictions were expanded for tighter export controls in January 2025, with ASML required to apply for export licenses with the Dutch government instead of the U.S.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In December 2025, Reuters reported that China had secretly built a prototype EUV machine in Shenzhen with the assistance of former ASML engineers, with the machine expected to produce working chips between 2028 and 2030.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML produces the photolithography machines used in the production of integrated circuits, called "scanners".
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In these machines, patterns are optically imaged onto a silicon wafer that is covered with a film of light-sensitive material (photoresist).
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] This procedure is repeated dozens of times on a single wafer.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The photoresist is then further processed to create the actual electronic circuits on the silicon.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The optical imaging that ASML's machines deal with is used in the fabrication of nearly all integrated circuits.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] As of 2025, ASML had 83% percent of the worldwide sales of lithography machines.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML's earlier competition consisted of Ultratech, Canon, Nikon, MKS Instruments, Lam Research and Cadence Design Systems.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Since immersion lithography was first proposed by Burn-Jeng Lin in the 1970s, ASML cooperated with TSMC.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 2004, TSMC began commercial production of 90 nanometer semiconductor nodes using ASML immersion lithography.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By 2011, their high-end TWINSCAN NXT:1950i system was used for producing features down to 32 nanometres at up to 200 wafers per hour, using a water immersion lens and an argon fluoride laser that produces light at a wavelength of 193 nm.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] By 2011, an average lithography machine cost €27 million.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Deep ultraviolet lithography (DUV) devices from ASML use ultraviolet light to print the tiny features that form the microchip's structure.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUV) is a critical technology used to create the smallest and most complex chip designs.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML holds a near-monopoly in the EUV market.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The company's machines are capable of etching patterns as small as 8 nanometers, 1/10000 the width of a human hair.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] EUV machines produce light in the 13.5 nm wavelength range by focusing a high-energy laser on microscopic droplets of molten tin to produce a plasma, which then emits EUV light.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The light is bounced off Zeiss mirrors onto the surface of a silicon wafer to form the designs for the chip.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] In 2009, the IMEC research center in Belgium produced the world's first functional 22 nm CMOS Static random-access memory memory cells with a prototype EUV lithography machine.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] After decades of development, ASML shipped the first production EUV machine in either 2011 or 2013.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] As of 2022, ASML has shipped around 140 EUV systems.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML's best-selling EUV product has been the TWINSCAN NXE:3600D, which costs up to $200 million.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The machine weighs 180 tons and needs three Boeing 747s to transport.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML is working on the next generation of EUV systems, with the first shipments for R&D shipped to Intel in December 2023, and TSMC in late 2024.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] The platform is designated *High-NA* as it increases the numerical aperture (NA) from 0.33 to 0.55. each system costs approximately $370 million.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML became a sponsor of the PSV football club in 2019 together with Philips, VDL Groep, Royal Swinkels Family Brewers and Jumbo Supermarkets from the Brainport region.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] Together they run various initiatives like soccer training camps for school children, the development of interactive programs for teaching, assisting community members in need or who are new to the region, as well as supporting a vitality program that is online.
[src:aex-index/asml-holding] ASML was the title partner of the Eindhoven marathon from 2022 - 2024.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] The original ASR insurance company was formed in 1997 after the merger of *Stad Rotterdam Verzekeringen* (which dates back to 1720) and *ETI Amersfoortse* insurance companies.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] The new name ASR was based on a combination of initials of Amersfoort and Stad Rotterdam.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] In 2000, Fortis acquired ASR insurance and merged it with its other insurance business to form **Fortis ASR**.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] At that time the other insurances business included the insurers *Amev*, *Ardanta* and *Falcon* (which included Interlloyd en VSB-leven).
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] In 2008, the insurance component became government owned when the Dutch Government took control of Fortis to prevent the bank and insurer from failing during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] On November 21, 2008, the Dutch Finance Minister, Wouter Bos announced that they would spin off Fortis Insurance Nederland NV using the revived name of **ASR Nederland NV**.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] In 2025 asr acquired the portfolio of Onderlinge van 1719, the oldest Dutch funeral insurance company.
[src:aex-index/asr-nederland] ASR operates from four locations with a headquarters in Utrecht.
[src:aex-index/nl] When cwi.nl was registered by Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica on 1986-05-01, .nl became the first active ccTLD outside the United States.
[src:aex-index/nl] Since 31 January 1996, .nl domains are registered by the Stichting Internet Domeinregistratie Nederland (SIDN, in English: Foundation for Internet Domain Registration Netherlands), based in Arnhem.
[src:aex-index/nl] Most registrars are Internet service providers, IT service bureaus and media service bureaus, but several large enterprises with many brand names have also become a registrar, or participant as SIDN calls them, which is a quite uncommon phenomenon in the domain name industry.
[src:aex-index/nl] Registrars have to pay SIDN a fee for each domain since 1 April 1996, until then registration was free.
[src:aex-index/nl] SIDN does not deal directly with registrants.
[src:aex-index/nl] In the early days, most of the registrants were universities and research departments of large companies, such as Philips Natuurkundig Laboratorium.
[src:aex-index/nl] Besides .nl, SIDN also operates .politie in a partnership with the Dutch police and .amsterdam in cooperation with the municipality of Amsterdam and Dotlocal.
[src:aex-index/nl] Official second-level domains do not exist.
[src:aex-index/nl] A number of companies have taken the opportunity to register domains like co.nl and com.nl, using them to sell third-level domains.
[src:aex-index/nl] Individuals were allowed to register a second-level .nl domain since 2003.
[src:aex-index/nl] As a forerunner, individuals were allowed to register a third-level domain since 2000.
[src:aex-index/nl] Such 'personal domains' had the form of janjansen.123.nl.
[src:aex-index/nl] They never became popular, and registration has been suspended since 2006.
[src:aex-index/nl] Because there were only around 500 of such domains registered, in contrast to about 5 million second-level domains, SIDN announced the discontinuance of personal domains as of 2008 on 4 July 2007.
[src:aex-index/nl] Unlike the majority of top level domains, .nl requires each nameserver to use a unique IP address.
[src:aex-index/nl] There must be at least two nameservers set, meaning at least two different IP addresses must be used.
[src:aex-index/nl] Other TLDs with this requirement are .ca and .cn.
